class TrieNode:
    def __init__(self):
        self.children = {}
        self.is_end_of_word = False

class Trie:
    def __init__(self):
        self.root = TrieNode()

    def insert(self, word):
        node = self.root
        for char in word:
            if char not in node.children:
                node.children[char] = TrieNode()
            node = node.children[char]
        node.is_end_of_word = True

    def search(self, word):
        node = self.root
        for char in word:
            if char not in node.children:
                return False
            node = node.children[char]
        return node.is_end_of_word

    def starts_with(self, prefix):
        node = self.root
        for char in prefix:
            if char not in node.children:
                return False
            node = node.children[char]
        return True

To read the entire catalog of a Shopify store using the Shopify APIs, you can use the Shopify API Node.js library (shopify-api-node) to interact with the APIs easily. Make sure you have the necessary access credentials (API key and password) for your store.

Here's a step-by-step guide:

1. First, install the "shopify-api-node" package:
```bash
npm install shopify-api-node
```
1. Create a new JavaScript file (e.g., `shopifyCatalog.js`) and import the required dependencies:
```javascript
const Shopify = require("shopify-api-node");
```
1. Set up the Shopify API credentials and create a new Shopify instance:
```javascript
const shopify = new Shopify({
  shopName: "your-shop-name",
  apiKey: "your-api-key",
  password: "your-api-password",
  autoLimit: true,
});
```
1. Create a function to fetch all products and their variants:
```javascript
async function fetchAllProducts() {
  let products = [];
  let params = { limit: 250 };

  do {
    const fetchedProducts = await shopify.product.list(params);
    products = products.concat(fetchedProducts);

    if (fetchedProducts.length < params.limit) break;

    const lastProductId = fetchedProducts[fetchedProducts.length - 1].id;
    params = { ...params, since_id: lastProductId };
  } while (true);

  return products;
}
```
1. Create a function to fetch all collections:
```javascript
async function fetchAllCollections(type = "custom") {
  let collections = [];
  let params = { limit: 250, type };

  do {
    const fetchedCollections = await shopify[`_${type}Collection`].list(params);
    collections = collections.concat(fetchedCollections);

    if (fetchedCollections.length < params.limit) break;

    const lastCollectionId = fetchedCollections[fetchedCollections.length - 1].id;
    params = { ...params, since_id: lastCollectionId };
  } while (true);

  return collections;
}
```
1. Call these functions and print the results:
```javascript
(async () => {
  try {
    const products = await fetchAllProducts();
    console.log("Products:", products);

    const customCollections = await fetchAllCollections("custom");
    console.log("Custom Collections:", customCollections);

    const smartCollections = await fetchAllCollections("smart");
    console.log("Smart Collections:", smartCollections);
  } catch (error) {
    console.error("Error fetching catalog:", error);
  }
})();
```
1. Replace the placeholders with your actual store credentials and run the script:
```bash
node shopifyCatalog.js
```
This script will fetch all products, custom collections, and smart collections from your Shopify store and print them to the console. Note that the rate limits for the Shopify API apply; the `autoLimit` option helps manage the rate limits automatically.

To place an order on Shopify for a selected product, you can follow these steps:

1. Make sure you have the "shopify-api-node" package installed:
```bash
npm install shopify-api-node
```
1. Create a new JavaScript file (e.g., `placeOrder.js`) and import the required dependencies:
```javascript
const Shopify = require("shopify-api-node");
```
1. Set up the Shopify API credentials and create a new Shopify instance:
```javascript
const shopify = new Shopify({
  shopName: "your-shop-name",
  apiKey: "your-api-key",
  password: "your-api-password",
  autoLimit: true,
});
```
1. Define a function to place an order for a product by providing a product variant ID, customer information, and shipping details:
```javascript
async function placeOrder(variantId, quantity, customer, shipping) {
  const order = {
    email: customer.email,
    fulfillment_status: "unfulfilled",
    send_receipt: true,
    send_fulfillment_receipt: true,
    line_items: [
      {
        variant_id: variantId,
        quantity: quantity,
      },
    ],
    customer: {
      first_name: customer.firstName,
      last_name: customer.lastName,
      email: customer.email,
    },
    shipping_address: {
      first_name: shipping.firstName,
      last_name: shipping.lastName,
      address1: shipping.address1,
      address2: shipping.address2,
      city: shipping.city,
      province: shipping.province,
      country: shipping.country,
      zip: shipping.zip,
      phone: shipping.phone,
    },
  };

  try {
    const newOrder = await shopify.order.create(order);
    return newOrder;
  } catch (error) {
    console.error("Error placing order:", error);
    return null;
  }
}
```
1. Call the `placeOrder` function with the required information:
```javascript
(async () => {
  const variantId = 1234567890; // Replace with your product variant ID
  const quantity = 1;

  const customer = {
    firstName: "John",
    lastName: "Doe",
    email: "john.doe@example.com",
  };

  const shipping = {
    firstName: "John",
    lastName: "Doe",
    address1: "123 Example Street",
    address2: "",
    city: "New York",
    province: "NY",
    country: "United States",
    zip: "10001",
    phone: "+1 (123) 456-7890",
  };

  const order = await placeOrder(variantId, quantity, customer, shipping);
  if (order) {
    console.log("Order placed successfully:", order);
